06784nam a22007455i 9780774856829DE-B159720240306124542.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||240306t19881988xxc    fo  d z      eng d  a97807748568297 a10.59962/97807748568292doi  a(DE-B1597)662236  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  axxccCA 4aVA400.R39 1988eb 7aHIS0060002bisacsh04a35900aRCN in Transition, 1910-1985 /ced. by W.A.B. Douglas. 1aVancouver ;aToronto : bUniversity of British Columbia Press, c[1988] 4c©1988  a1 online resource (422 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda00tFront Matter -- tContents -- tAbbreviations -- tIntroduction: The Canadian Navy in the Modern World -- tNaval Mastery: The Canadian Context -- tStrategy and Maritime Law: “Free Seas” and the Canadian Navy -- tHistorical Strategy and Its Uses in Large and Small Navies -- tMarcom Education: Is it a Break with Tradition? -- tThe End of Pax Britannica and the Origins of the Royal Canadian Navy: Shifting Strategic Demands of an Empire at Sea -- tHard Luck Flotilla: The RCN’s Atlantic Coast Patrol, 1914–18 -- tInshore Asw in the Second World War: The U-Boat Experience -- tInshore Asw: The Canadian Experience in Home Waters -- tCanada and the Wolf Packs, September 1943 -- tThe “St Laurent” Decision: Genesis of a Canadian Fleet -- tCanada and the Cold War at Sea, 1945–68 -- tInternational Naval Co-Operation and Admiral Richard G. Colbert: The Intertwining of a Career with an Idea -- tEconomic Considerations in the Development of the Canadian Navy Since 1945 -- tCanadian Naval Responsibilities in the Arctic -- tShips: Managing the Need -- tCanada and Maritime Defence: Past Problems, Future Challenges* -- tThe Future of Naval Warfare -- tNotes -- tContributors -- tIndex0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis book is about the life of a navy, from its conception in the nineteenth century to its seventy-fifth birthday in 1985. Born in the midst of political controversy, the Royal Canadian Navy traces its roots to conflicting British and Canadian interests during the prime ministerships of Sir John A. Macdonald and Sir Wilfrid Laurier, as well as to Anglo-German naval competition in the early years of the twentieth century. The RCN played a more important role in World War I than has generally been realized and, despite neglect between the wars, rose to a position of some prominence in World War II. Except for a demoralizing period of retrenchment from 1945 to 1949, it then flourished until the early 1960's, before the twin agonies of unification and defence cutbacks began to influence its development. Total unification of the navy with the army and air force has been a unique Canadian experience. How Canada weathered the transition from RCN to "Marine Command" is illuminated by the discussions in this book. The navy appears as a resilient institution in the face of change, particularly in the last two decades of its first seventy-five years. This collection of papers by leading authorities in naval history and defence policy provides a record of Canadian naval problems, the navy's pragmatic search for solutions, and its prospects for the future. The authors open up areas of discussion that will be of fundamental importance in the critical years to come.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 06. Mrz 2024) 7aHISTORY / Canada / General.2bisacsh1 aByers, R.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCritchley, Harriet, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDavis, S. Mathwin, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, W.A.B., econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDouglas, W.A.B., eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc